{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Only files changed in the pull request are analyzed — unchanged files are not scanned.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is the handoff between PR-changed-file collection and analysis orchestration (cross-module state propagation). Unit is too low because a pure filter function passing does not prove the orchestrator only schedules changed files. System was considered but rejected: behavior text does not require validating real network/OS/subprocess effects, only correct module wiring of file selection.","test_description":"Wire the PR file-list provider module to the analysis scheduler in-process (with a fake PR diff payload containing changed + unchanged paths) and assert only changed paths are dispatched to scanning.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.67,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Findings are grouped by severity (error, warning, info) in the posted PR comment.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real risk is at module boundaries: linter findings -> grouping/formatting -> PR comment payload. A unit test of grouping alone can miss serialization/template wiring defects. Agentic/Workflow are disqualified because no AI decision is involved. System was considered but rejected: posting can be stubbed; behavior text focuses on grouping correctness in comment content, not real HTTP behavior.","test_description":"Run findings parser, severity grouper, and comment renderer together with a stub PR-comment client; assert final posted body contains correctly separated error/warning/info sections and expected findings under each.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A pull request that touches 200 files completes analysis within the 10-minute Actions timeout.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly targets CI runtime bound tied to GitHub Actions timeout; this is a real infrastructure/performance boundary (process scheduling, I/O, subprocess execution time). Integration with fakes can understate latency and hide timeout failures. Higher levels (Agentic/Workflow) are disqualified by behavior text: no AI/ML steps.","test_description":"Execute the lint step as an actual job-like system test (real linter subprocesses and filesystem corpus approximating 200 changed files) and assert end-to-end wall-clock completion is under 10 minutes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.83,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the linter process crashes on a malformed file, the remaining files are still analyzed and results posted.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure mode depends on real subprocess crash semantics and supervisor recovery behavior. Mocking process execution can hide true crash handling (exit codes/signals/pipe teardown). Integration is too low because behavior text explicitly says 'linter process crashes'. Higher levels (Agentic/Workflow) are disqualified: no model-driven decisions.","test_description":"Run orchestrator against a file set where one input triggers an actual crashing linter subprocess; verify orchestrator records the crash, continues analyzing subsequent files, and emits a final PR-results payload.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.88,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate findings on the same line from overlapping rules are deduplicated in the output.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior is primarily deterministic dedup logic over finding records (same file/line/rule overlap criteria) within one local